00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.430
This this type of cartoon.

00:29:23.430 --> 00:29:27.870
This type of discourse is
through the media in these years.

00:29:27.870 --> 00:29:32.590
And much of this discourse
focused on apartments.

00:29:32.590 --> 00:29:38.580
Since 1954, the party began
to make massive investments

00:29:38.580 --> 00:29:41.620
in workers apartment buildings,
transforming cityscapes

00:29:41.620 --> 00:29:44.690
of the peninsula, as
I hinted at earlier.

00:29:44.690 --> 00:29:46.840
Yet, despite all the celebration

00:29:46.840 --> 00:29:50.920
of how these apartments represented
the success of the revolution,

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:54.260
the press was much more comfortable
about treating these buildings

00:29:54.260 --> 00:29:58.580
in terms of the construction
rather than their inhabitation.

00:29:58.580 --> 00:30:01.800
Thus, you get this
type of photograph.

00:30:01.800 --> 00:30:04.300
It's about the monumentality
of the building.

00:30:04.300 --> 00:30:07.180
The pictures are generally
from outside.

00:30:07.180 --> 00:30:12.800
When photographers did
venture into apartments,

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:18.610
the photos are almost always
cropped, closely onto a family

00:30:18.610 --> 00:30:22.810
in a genre that might be
called the happy family photo

00:30:22.810 --> 00:30:26.070
without really allowing
the camera to pan

00:30:26.070 --> 00:30:28.250
across the space of the apartment.

00:30:28.250 --> 00:30:31.290
There's a certain reticence
to show the apartment

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:32.590
as a space of consumption.

00:30:32.590 --> 00:30:36.130
And indeed, there's a
critique at this time,

00:30:36.130 --> 00:30:41.200
as we can see in this cartoon
here there's sort of a fear

00:30:41.200 --> 00:30:44.110
that women would get too
comfortable inside the apartments

00:30:44.110 --> 00:30:45.960
and not be interested
in going out to work.

00:30:45.960 --> 00:30:49.810
And here's one where we can see
at the top a woman is sleeping in,

00:30:49.810 --> 00:30:52.820
and she's doing her makeup
and her sort of comfort

00:30:52.820 --> 00:30:56.070
in his apartment space that
makes her late taking her kid.

00:30:56.070 --> 00:31:00.890
All right complaining at the end.

00:31:00.890 --> 00:31:03.240
So again, there's this
reticence to show the apartment

00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:05.540
as a space of consumption.

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:08.730
Here I'm going to make a bit
of a jump and jump to the 1960s

00:31:08.730 --> 00:31:12.580
where you get a shift, and
the shift is quite stunning,

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:14.410
I only saw it last time I was here

00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:18.370
at the Library of Congress
in November.

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:21.890
There are two specific journals
called [foreign words], New Life,

00:31:21.890 --> 00:31:30.320
that begin in 1963, and I'm
not quite sure why it's 1963.

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:35.530
Suddenly offering long
and many articles

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.640
of what we would today
call lifestyle coverage.

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:44.460
As one article in this period
asked, where does a rooms sense

00:31:44.460 --> 00:31:49.120
of harmonious beauty or taste of
cultural refinement come from.

00:31:49.120 --> 00:31:51.780
That's not easy to
answer in a few words.

00:31:51.780 --> 00:31:54.460
And indeed, there were many
words in these pages later

00:31:54.460 --> 00:31:55.980
to try and talk about this.

00:31:55.980 --> 00:31:59.130
That type of question where it's
invoking cultural refinement,

00:31:59.130 --> 00:32:02.810
harmonious beauty, would
just had no presence

00:32:02.810 --> 00:32:05.780
in the press just a
few years earlier.

00:32:05.780 --> 00:32:07.790
So, these articles talked about how

00:32:07.790 --> 00:32:11.510
to arrange the furniture
in one's home right.

00:32:11.510 --> 00:32:18.320
They began to discuss how to
hang pictures on the wall.

00:32:18.320 --> 00:32:20.740
Should you have vertical
versus horizontal pictures.

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:25.120
Should you have sunlight
or curtains.

00:32:25.120 --> 00:32:30.080
Clearly the preference for pictures
were landscapes there's discussions

00:32:30.080 --> 00:32:34.010
about what color is best for what
type of room or even color charts

00:32:34.010 --> 00:32:36.640
for people to choose from.

00:32:36.640 --> 00:32:42.070
By this point we get no sense
of reticence or ill at ease.

00:32:42.070 --> 00:32:45.740 position:56%
In fact, when you look at these type
of pictures you can begin to see

00:32:45.740 --> 00:32:51.010 position:56%
that the camera is taking a step
back and it's beginning to show more

00:32:51.010 --> 00:32:56.660
about the objects through which
people lived their everyday life.

00:32:56.660 --> 00:33:02.920
Right? So, here's one chockablock
would not have met the design

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:04.800
criteria of any article
I've ever read

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:10.580
in North Korean presses too jammed
with tables and plants, right.

00:33:10.580 --> 00:33:12.970
Here's another one and
here this is featuring two

00:33:12.970 --> 00:33:15.120
of the main consumer
items from this period,

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:17.850
the radio in the sewing machine.

00:33:17.850 --> 00:33:20.960
So, very much a well-off family.

00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:24.920
Right? Anybody know what's in
the middle of the table there?

00:33:24.920 --> 00:33:31.540
Goldfish. This goes as well for
the way furniture is discussed.

00:33:31.540 --> 00:33:32.840
You can see these ones.

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:34.140
There's absolutely no people.

00:33:34.140 --> 00:33:35.440
You can see the painting.

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:38.400
You can see that there's no Kim
LLsung portrait on the wall.

00:33:42.250 --> 00:33:44.120
Again, a very different sensibility

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:47.060
of what could have been
discussed in an earlier period.

00:33:47.060 --> 00:33:50.170
This transfers over
to fashions as well.

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:51.850
In particular, women's clothing.

00:33:51.850 --> 00:33:54.490
I'm not going to talk about this,
because I'm running out of time,

00:33:54.490 --> 00:33:59.830
but I just want to show you some
of these images from this period.

00:33:59.830 --> 00:34:07.610
And we can see that there begins in
the 1960s new forms of femininity

00:34:07.610 --> 00:34:11.230
that have a lot to do
with new forms of clothing

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:16.830
that aren't the typical here's one
of the color charts for clothing.

00:34:25.620 --> 00:34:30.310
So we have these new forms of
femininity that don't fit into what

00:34:30.310 --> 00:34:34.830 position:56%
until this point fashion had largely
been either your work uniform

00:34:34.830 --> 00:34:38.180 position:56%
or you know the [foreign word] what
in South Korea is called the hanbok,

00:34:38.180 --> 00:34:40.600
the traditional Korean dress.

00:34:40.600 --> 00:34:43.500
There are all sorts of questions
that we can ask about these types

00:34:43.500 --> 00:34:46.000
of images, these types
of consumption, right.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:49.580
We can ask legitimately how many
people were actually consuming

00:34:49.580 --> 00:34:50.880
like this, right?

00:34:50.880 --> 00:34:53.470
We don't have good answers for.

00:34:53.470 --> 00:34:56.000
We can also ask what did it mean

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:57.880
that this was being
publicly discussed right.

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:00.300
This isn't a type of
secret form of consumption

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:03.720
that only high party officials
are doing behind closed doors.

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:06.730
These are pictures that are
circulating in magazines

00:35:06.730 --> 00:35:08.440
that have tens of thousands,
some of them have

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:12.990
over 100,000 copies being printed.

00:35:12.990 --> 00:35:15.910
Just like in this country, even
if you can't afford everything

00:35:15.910 --> 00:35:18.750
that you see in the magazine
you can consume the images right

00:35:18.750 --> 00:35:20.130
and the promise of
what this might mean

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:23.290
about the future, about
possibilities.

00:35:23.290 --> 00:35:25.220
We can ask what does
this consumption mean

00:35:25.220 --> 00:35:29.850
about postwar class formations
and uneven distribution of goods.

00:35:29.850 --> 00:35:33.090
It's also possible that we wonder
whether there were certain groups

00:35:33.090 --> 00:35:36.640
that taking advantage of that
ambivalence towards consumption

00:35:36.640 --> 00:35:40.410
that I spoke of earlier pushed
the promise of material comfort

00:35:40.410 --> 00:35:45.130
to create a space to speak
of consumption in new ways.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:49.040
This would put these consumers, or
these writers about consumption,

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:52.020
together with the factory
managers and the urban migrants,

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:56.930
that I spoke about in my earlier
case study as people whose behavior

00:35:56.930 --> 00:36:00.050
in these important rounds
moves beyond the type

00:36:00.050 --> 00:36:03.130
of top-down directives of
the leadership in the party.

00:36:03.130 --> 00:36:06.410
In other words, another
location of historical agency.

00:36:06.410 --> 00:36:09.690
However one chooses to
interpret this consumption,

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:13.580
one thing is clear is if we're to
read Kim's speeches the resolutions

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:17.650
of party congresses or even the
main newspaper, the [foreign word],

00:36:17.650 --> 00:36:19.660
right we would miss out completely

00:36:19.660 --> 00:36:23.320
on the significant economic
and cultural changes.

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:29.310
So, the problem I described earlier
of taking intentions as outcomes,

00:36:29.310 --> 00:36:33.110
we can add the further problem
of simply not looking in places

00:36:33.110 --> 00:36:37.000
where we can locate
socioeconomic and cultural changes.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.810 position:56%
Ones that are not being unilaterally
produced by the leadership

00:36:39.810 --> 00:36:42.700
or the party, but which
in fact contribute

00:36:42.700 --> 00:36:46.950
to shaping the possibilities of
postwar politics in North Korea.

00:36:46.950 --> 00:36:50.520
So, let me conclude by doing
what a historian should never do,

00:36:50.520 --> 00:36:54.790
make a few comments about the
current situation in North Korea.

00:36:54.790 --> 00:36:59.710
Most observers know that since the
early 1990s there have been a lot

00:36:59.710 --> 00:37:01.960
of changes afoot in North Korea.

00:37:01.960 --> 00:37:06.040
Some of the indications of these
changes commentators often speak

00:37:06.040 --> 00:37:08.380
about, what population mobility.

00:37:08.380 --> 00:37:10.990
People are moving around
in lots of new ways.

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:15.260
New forms of consumption, where
women's fashions are often talked

00:37:15.260 --> 00:37:17.630
about as are the new
style of apartments

00:37:17.630 --> 00:37:19.010
that are going up in city.

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:21.600
There are many more, I just wanted
to highlight that the three areas

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.670
that I sort of talked about in
this talk, are referred to today

00:37:24.670 --> 00:37:27.630
in order to track changes.

00:37:27.630 --> 00:37:32.370 position:56%
These changes are often read as
indicating a decline in the capacity

00:37:32.370 --> 00:37:34.640
of the state to rule
the country right.

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:37.730
People are doing stuff that
the state doesn't want to.

00:37:37.730 --> 00:37:39.660
Some commentators go so far

00:37:39.660 --> 00:37:42.170
as to predict the imminent
collapse of North Korea.

00:37:42.170 --> 00:37:44.140
We know that going back
to the Clinton years

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:47.970
at least this assumption
even shaped certain parts

00:37:47.970 --> 00:37:50.510
of American policy
towards the north.

00:37:50.510 --> 00:37:55.710 position:56%
Now as a historian, I'm not in the
business of making predictions other

00:37:55.710 --> 00:37:58.060
than knowing that if you
continue over decades

00:37:58.060 --> 00:38:01.050
to predict the collapse, you
eventually might be right.

00:38:01.050 --> 00:38:04.840
I can't help but notice that
these predictions of the demise

00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:08.310
of the North Korean state
often take as a background

00:38:08.310 --> 00:38:12.180
against which they measure these
changes the very cartoonish

00:38:12.180 --> 00:38:15.510
understanding of North Korean
history that have attempted to draw

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:21.250
out that concentric totalitarian no
alternative historical agency type

00:38:21.250 --> 00:38:23.060
of history.

00:38:23.060 --> 00:38:26.380
Yet if you consider the history of
population movement and consumption

00:38:26.380 --> 00:38:27.970
to try to offer you today,

00:38:27.970 --> 00:38:31.850
we can see that there's always
been a much more complicated

00:38:31.850 --> 00:38:34.860 position:56%
and fluid history in the
relationship between the Kim family,

00:38:34.860 --> 00:38:39.080
the different segments and levels
of the state, and the population.

00:38:39.080 --> 00:38:43.460
If we escape the type of Cold War
era style histories of North Korea,

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:45.630 position:56%
then the context of the many changes

00:38:45.630 --> 00:38:50.080
that are being remarked
upon today begins to shift.

00:38:50.080 --> 00:38:56.180
And so, the meaning of today's
changes also begins to shift.

00:38:56.180 --> 00:39:00.100
Always there have been limits
on state power in North Korea.

00:39:00.100 --> 00:39:04.290
The state has always had to
adjust to changes in social

00:39:04.290 --> 00:39:12.300
and economic forces, and one of
the virtues of this collection

00:39:12.300 --> 00:39:15.700
at the Library of Congress is that
it allows us actually to begin

00:39:15.700 --> 00:39:19.970
to try and explore some of these
other areas of historical agency.

00:39:19.970 --> 00:39:24.140
Some of the social, economic,
cultural, and gendered forces

00:39:24.140 --> 00:39:27.400
that shape the history
with which the party,

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:31.500
with which the Kim family is
actually having to deal with.

00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:32.940
And I'll conclude my remarks there

00:39:32.940 --> 00:39:34.760
and I'd be happy to
take any questions.

00:39:34.760 --> 00:39:36.560
Thank you.

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:42.590
[ Applause ]

00:39:42.590 --> 00:39:45.820
Yes, in the back there please?

00:39:45.820 --> 00:39:47.620
Could you tell me your name, maybe?

00:39:47.620 --> 00:40:39.640
[ Inaudible Audience Question ]

00:40:39.640 --> 00:40:41.500 position:56%
Right, it's a great question, right.

00:40:41.500 --> 00:40:43.540
Because especially in the '50s

00:40:43.540 --> 00:40:46.920
and the 1960s North
Korea sees itself firmly

00:40:46.920 --> 00:40:48.820
within a socialist word.

00:40:48.820 --> 00:40:53.250
There is all sorts of circulations
of movies and magazines.

00:40:53.250 --> 00:40:55.140
North Koreans are participating

00:40:55.140 --> 00:40:58.140
in conferences throughout
the eastern bloc.

00:40:58.140 --> 00:41:02.320
And I think the trick to
answering your question is partly

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:05.380
which eastern European, or which
other socialist country you're

00:41:05.380 --> 00:41:07.730
comparing with because
there's an enormous variety

00:41:07.730 --> 00:41:10.030
of these questions
within socialist blocks.

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:16.110 position:56%
So, one place I would start would be
for example, the design of housing.

00:41:16.110 --> 00:41:22.910
So, one of the things we could
find in the library here is

00:41:22.910 --> 00:41:31.830 position:56%
that there are architecture journals
where we can see all the types

00:41:31.830 --> 00:41:39.770
of designs of apartments that are
being constructed in North Korea.

00:41:39.770 --> 00:41:47.670
And even all sorts of models that
were never actually constructed.

00:41:47.670 --> 00:41:56.640
We see that somebody, I don't think
there was a single decision made

00:41:56.640 --> 00:42:04.600
on this, but there is no
communal housing in North Korea.

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:08.810
It's all designed for the
single nuclear family.

00:42:08.810 --> 00:42:11.540
It's two rooms, a kitchen,
a bathroom,

00:42:11.540 --> 00:42:15.690
and you can shut the
apartment door, right?

00:42:15.690 --> 00:42:27.310 position:56%
So, unlike in China, if that's our
comparison, it's right at this point

00:42:27.310 --> 00:42:31.770
in China of course that communal
housing is being developed.

00:42:31.770 --> 00:42:37.380
Very different from the
situation in North Korea.

00:42:37.380 --> 00:42:39.920
So, in China the assumption

00:42:39.920 --> 00:42:44.980
that this architecture design could
help breakdown, or weaken the bonds

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:49.430
of the family because it's
considered to be the bastion

00:42:49.430 --> 00:42:54.480
of futile values or
Confucian values, right?

00:42:54.480 --> 00:42:58.680
In North Korea, and
I think it's partly

00:42:58.680 --> 00:43:03.580
because of the colonial experience
in North Korea, there is an attempt

00:43:03.580 --> 00:43:05.870
to use architecture to firm up
the nuclear family actually.

00:43:05.870 --> 00:43:07.250
If I were then to look at
the designs with what's going

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:08.550
on in the Soviet Union
at this period,

00:43:08.550 --> 00:43:09.850
we know that Khrushchev
right at this moment is part

00:43:09.850 --> 00:43:11.540
of his anti-Stalinist drive is
actually using everyday life design

00:43:11.540 --> 00:43:12.840
and material comfort
as one of the ways

00:43:12.840 --> 00:43:14.450
of criticizing the Stalinist era
and opening up new possibilities

00:43:14.450 --> 00:43:15.750
for the Soviet population.

00:43:15.750 --> 00:43:17.050
What we see going on in North
Korea is more in tune with that.

00:43:17.050 --> 00:43:18.350
So, you see the circulation

00:43:18.350 --> 00:43:19.650
of housing designs,
or these exhibitions.

00:43:19.650 --> 00:43:20.950 position:56%
But, there's an important
distinction is that the Soviet Union

00:43:20.950 --> 00:43:22.250
in its cities it's much
wealthier than North Korea, right?

00:43:22.250 --> 00:43:23.550
So, in terms of the material
culture, the objects,

00:43:23.550 --> 00:43:24.850
I think there's no
comparison, and even less though

00:43:24.850 --> 00:43:26.150
with east Germany, right?

00:43:26.150 --> 00:43:27.450
so, you're right that it's
important to see North Korea

00:43:27.450 --> 00:43:28.750
in that broader socialist
world context.

00:43:28.750 --> 00:43:30.050
But we have to also be
careful that there's a lot

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:31.350
of variety within that context.

00:43:31.350 --> 00:43:32.650
I've always been curious
what's going

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:33.950
on in Cuba at this particular time.

00:43:33.950 --> 00:43:35.750
I don't know that but, yes?

00:43:35.750 --> 00:43:56.080
[ Inaudible Audience Question ]

00:43:56.080 --> 00:43:59.490
So, you know my sense is that there
aren't as many links with China

00:43:59.490 --> 00:44:03.760
as there are with the eastern bloc.

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:09.060
Partly, you have to remember
that the North Koreans set

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:13.270
up their country in 1945 four
years before the revolution, right?

00:44:13.270 --> 00:44:19.670
And so, there's actually this sense
that we got there first in a way.

00:44:19.670 --> 00:44:25.930 position:56%
Through the 1950s, so let me address
your question by maybe talking

00:44:25.930 --> 00:44:27.610
about fashion, women's fashion.

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:31.700
My understanding of most of the
literature on the People's Republic

00:44:31.700 --> 00:44:37.150
of China is that scholars emphasize
how after the revolution there was

00:44:37.150 --> 00:44:42.580
that sort of de-feminization
of women in China,

00:44:42.580 --> 00:44:53.420
but for the most part dress
becomes more masculine orientation.

00:44:53.420 --> 00:44:59.130 position:56%
There's less emphasis on femininity.

00:44:59.130 --> 00:45:01.920
North Korea, that never happens.

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:08.130
If anything, what happens
after the declaration

00:45:08.130 --> 00:45:13.360
of equality this would
have been 1946,

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:18.190
North Korea is the first country
in Asia to declare the equality

00:45:18.190 --> 00:45:19.680
of the two genders, right?

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:30.470
And while you have that druidical
influence, emphasis on equality,

00:45:30.470 --> 00:45:37.560
you've got all sorts of
other ways of speaking

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:43.230
about femininity, naturalizing
femininity.

00:45:43.230 --> 00:45:47.380
So, in North Korea for
example, there's an emphasis

00:45:47.380 --> 00:45:48.680
on the way women speak,
speech is promoted,

00:45:48.680 --> 00:45:50.260
there are specific feminine ways
to speak, which is an important way

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:51.730
of naturalizing gender
difference, which becomes important

00:45:51.730 --> 00:45:53.030 position:56%
for the segregation of labor, right?

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:54.330
There's all sorts of complications

00:45:54.330 --> 00:45:55.630
when we begin naturalizing
that distinction.

00:45:55.630 --> 00:45:56.930
So, unlike with China the issue

00:45:56.930 --> 00:45:58.230
with the way femininity
is being promoted,

00:45:58.230 --> 00:45:59.530
actually becomes very important

